# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: n-body-simulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] When matter becomes sufficiently hot and energetic, it becomes ionized and forms a plasma.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] This process breaks matter into its constituent particles which includes negatively charged electrons and positively charged ions.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] These electrically charged particles are susceptible to influences by local electromagnetic fields.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] This includes strong fields generated by stars, and weak fields which exist in star forming regions, in interstellar space, and in intergalactic space.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Similarly, electric fields are observed in some stellar astrophysical phenomena.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Astrophysical plasma is often differentiated from space plasma, which typically refers to the plasma of the Sun, the solar wind, and the ionospheres and magnetospheres of the Earth and other planets.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Although gas and plasma are distinct states of matter, the term *gas* is frequently used by astronomers to refer to any astrophysical fluid that is in either the gas or plasma state of matter.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] The term *ionized gas* specifically refers to plasma.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Plasmas in stars can both generate and interact with magnetic fields, resulting in a variety of dynamic astrophysical phenomena.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] These phenomena are sometimes observed in spectra due to the Zeeman effect.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Other forms of astrophysical plasmas can be influenced by preexisting weak magnetic fields, whose interactions may only be determined directly by polarimetry or other indirect methods.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] In particular, the intergalactic medium, the interstellar medium, the interplanetary medium and solar winds consist of diffuse plasmas.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Scientists are interested in active galactic nuclei because such astrophysical plasmas could be directly related to the plasmas studied in laboratories.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Many of these phenomena seemingly exhibit an array of complex magnetohydrodynamic behaviors, such as turbulence and instabilities.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] In Big Bang cosmology, the entire universe was in a plasma state prior to recombination.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Norwegian explorer and physicist Kristian Birkeland predicted that space is filled with plasma.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] Birkeland assumed that most of the mass in the universe should be found in "empty" space.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] The 1959 album *Space Songs* contains the song *Why Does the Sun Shine?*, which incorrectly refers to the Sun as "a mass of incandescent gas." In 1993, They Might Be Giants released a cover version of this song in an EP entitled *Why Does the Sun Shine?
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] (The Sun Is a Mass of Incandescent Gas)*.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] The album *Here Comes Science* was released by They Might be Giants in 2009.
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] *Here Comes Science* includes a recording of this song immediately followed by the song *Why Does the Sun Really Shine?
[src:n-body-simulation/astrophysical-plasma] (The Sun is a Miasma of Incandescent Plasma)* that correctly refers to the Sun as plasma.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] The **Barnes–Hut simulation** (named after Joshua Barnes and Piet Hut) is an approximation algorithm for performing an N-body simulation.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] It is notable for having order O(*n* log *n*) compared to a direct-sum algorithm which would be O(*n*2).
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] This can dramatically reduce the number of particle pair interactions that must be computed.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] Some of the most demanding high-performance computing projects perform computational astrophysics using the Barnes–Hut treecode algorithm, such as DEGIMA.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] In a three-dimensional *N*-body simulation, the Barnes–Hut algorithm recursively divides the *n* bodies into groups by storing them in an octree (or a quad-tree in a 2D simulation).
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] Each node in this tree represents a region of the three-dimensional space.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] The topmost node represents the whole space, and its eight children represent the eight octants of the space.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] The space is recursively subdivided into octants until each subdivision contains 0 or 1 bodies (some regions do not have bodies in all of their octants).
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] There are two types of nodes in the octree: internal and external nodes.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] An external node has no children and is either empty or represents a single body.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] Each internal node represents the group of bodies beneath it, and stores the center of mass and the total mass of all its children bodies.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] To calculate the net force on a particular body, the nodes of the tree are traversed, starting from the root.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] If the center of mass of an internal node is sufficiently far from the body, the bodies contained in that part of the tree are treated as a single particle whose position and mass is respectively the center of mass and total mass of the internal node.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] If the internal node is sufficiently close to the body, the process is repeated for each of its children.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] Whether a node is or isn't sufficiently far away from a body, depends on the quotient $s/d$ , where *s* is the width of the region represented by the internal node, and *d* is the distance between the body and the node's center of mass.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] The node is sufficiently far away when this ratio is smaller than a threshold value *θ*.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] The parameter *θ* determines the accuracy of the simulation; larger values of *θ* increase the speed of the simulation but decreases its accuracy.
[src:n-body-simulation/barnes-hut-simulation] If *θ* = 0, no internal node is treated as a single body and the algorithm degenerates to a direct-sum algorithm.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The **fast multipole method** (**FMM**) is a numerical technique that was developed to speed up the calculation of long-ranged forces in the *n*-body problem.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] It does this by expanding the system Green's function using a multipole expansion, which allows one to group sources that lie close together and treat them as if they were a single source.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The FMM has also been applied in accelerating the iterative solver in the method of moments (MoM) as applied to computational electromagnetics problems, and in particular in computational bioelectromagnetism.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The FMM was first introduced in this manner by Leslie Greengard and Vladimir Rokhlin Jr. and is based on the multipole expansion of the vector Helmholtz equation.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] By treating the interactions between far-away basis functions using the FMM, the corresponding matrix elements do not need to be explicitly stored, resulting in a significant reduction in required memory.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] This has expanded the area of applicability of the MOM to far greater problems than were previously possible.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The FMM, introduced by Rokhlin Jr. and Greengard has been said to be one of the top ten algorithms of the 20th century.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The FMM algorithm reduces the complexity of matrix-vector multiplication involving a certain type of dense matrix which can arise out of many physical systems.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The FMM has also been applied for efficiently treating the Coulomb interaction in the Hartree–Fock method and density functional theory calculations in quantum chemistry.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] This is the one-dimensional form of the problem, but the algorithm can be easily generalized to multiple dimensions and kernels other than $(y-x)^{-1}$ .
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] Naively, evaluating $f(y)$ on M points requires ${\mathcal {O}}(MN)$ operations.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] The crucial observation behind the fast multipole method is that if the distance between y and x is large enough, then $(y-x)^{-1}$ is well-approximated by a polynomial.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] Specifically, let $-1<t_{1}<\ldots <t_{p}<1$ be the Chebyshev nodes of order $p\geq 2,$ and let $u_{1}(y),\ldots ,u_{p}(y)$ be the corresponding Lagrange basis polynomials.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] One can show that the interpolating polynomial ${\frac {1}{y-x}}=\sum _{i=1}^{p}{\frac {1}{t_{i}-x}}u_{i}(y)+\epsilon _{p}(y)$ converges quickly with polynomial order, $|\epsilon _{p(y)}|<5^{-p}$ , provided that the pole is far enough away from the region of interpolation, $|x|\geq 3$ and $|y|<1$ .
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] Since $p=-\log _{5}\epsilon$ , where $\epsilon$ is the numerical tolerance, the total cost is ${\mathcal {O}}{\big (}(M+N)\log(1/\epsilon ){\big )}$ .
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] To ensure that the poles are indeed well-separated, one recursively subdivides the unit interval such that only ${\mathcal {O}}(p)$ poles end up in each interval.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] One then uses the explicit formula within each interval and interpolation for all intervals that are well-separated.
[src:n-body-simulation/fast-multipole-method] This does not spoil the scaling, since one needs at most $\log(1/\epsilon )$ levels within the given tolerance.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] In classical mechanics, the **gravitational potential** is a scalar potential associating with each point in space the work (energy transferred) per unit mass that would be needed to move an object to that point from a fixed reference point in the conservative gravitational field.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] It is analogous to the electric potential with mass playing the role of charge.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The reference point, where the potential is zero, is by convention infinitely far away from any mass, resulting in a negative potential at any finite distance.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Their similarity is correlated with both associated fields having conservative forces.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Mathematically, the gravitational potential is also known as the Newtonian potential and is fundamental in the study of potential theory.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] It may also be used for solving the electrostatic and magnetostatic fields generated by uniformly charged or polarized ellipsoidal bodies.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Potential energy is equal (in magnitude, but negative) to the work done by the gravitational field moving a body to its given position in space from infinity.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] If the body has a mass of 1 kilogram, then the potential energy to be assigned to that body is equal to the gravitational potential.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] So the potential can be interpreted as the negative of the work done by the gravitational field moving a unit mass in from infinity.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] In some situations, the equations can be simplified by assuming a field that is nearly independent of position.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] For instance, in a region close to the surface of the Earth, the gravitational acceleration, *g*, can be considered constant.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The product *GM* is the standard gravitational parameter and is often known to higher precision than *G* or *M* separately.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The potential has units of energy per mass, e.g., J/kg in the MKS system.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] By convention, it is always negative where it is defined, and as *x* tends to infinity, it approaches zero.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The gravitational field, and thus the acceleration of a small body in the space around the massive object, is the negative gradient of the gravitational potential.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Thus the negative of a negative gradient yields positive acceleration toward a massive object.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The potential associated with a mass distribution is the superposition of the potentials of point masses.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] If the mass distribution is given as a mass measure *dm* on three-dimensional Euclidean space **R**3, then the potential is the convolution of −*G*/|**r**| with *dm*.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] If *V* is a potential function coming from a continuous mass distribution *ρ*(**r**), then *ρ* can be recovered using the Laplace operator, Δ: $\rho (\mathbf {x} )={\frac {1}{4\pi G}}\Delta V(\mathbf {x} ).$ This holds pointwise whenever *ρ* is continuous and is zero outside of a bounded set.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] In general, the mass measure *dm* can be recovered in the same way if the Laplace operator is taken in the sense of distributions.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] As a consequence, the gravitational potential satisfies Poisson's equation.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] See also Green's function for the three-variable Laplace equation and Newtonian potential.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The integral may be expressed in terms of known transcendental functions for all ellipsoidal shapes, including the symmetrical and degenerate ones.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] All these shapes are widely used in the applications of the gravitational potential integral (apart from the constant *G*, with 𝜌 being a constant charge density) to electromagnetism.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] A spherically symmetric mass distribution behaves to an observer completely outside the distribution as though all of the mass was concentrated at the center, and thus effectively as a point mass, by the shell theorem.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] On the surface of the earth, the acceleration is given by so-called standard gravity *g*, approximately 9.8 m/s2, although this value varies slightly with latitude and altitude.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The magnitude of the acceleration is a little larger at the poles than at the equator because Earth is an oblate spheroid.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Within a spherically symmetric mass distribution, it is possible to solve Poisson's equation in spherical coordinates.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] In general relativity, the gravitational potential is replaced by the metric tensor.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] When the gravitational field is weak and the sources are moving very slowly compared to light-speed, general relativity reduces to Newtonian gravity, and the metric tensor can be expanded in terms of the gravitational potential.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The potential can be expanded in a series of Legendre polynomials.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Represent the points **x** and **r** as position vectors relative to the center of mass.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] (See *§ Mathematical form*.) The integrand can be expanded as a Taylor series in *Z* = *r*/|**x**|, by explicit calculation of the coefficients.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] A less laborious way of achieving the same result is by using the generalized binomial theorem.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The coefficients *P**n* are the Legendre polynomials of degree *n*.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] Therefore, the Taylor coefficients of the integrand are given by the Legendre polynomials in *X* = cos *θ*.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] This shows that elongation of the body causes a lower potential in the direction of elongation, and a higher potential in perpendicular directions, compared to the potential due to a spherical mass, if we compare cases with the same distance to the center of mass.
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The SI unit of gravitational potential is the square metre per square second (m2/s2) or, equivalently, the joule per kilogram (J/kg).
[src:n-body-simulation/gravitational-potential] The potential is half the square of the escape velocity.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] In physics and astronomy, an ***N*-body simulation** is a simulation of a dynamical system of particles, usually under the influence of physical forces, such as gravity (see *n*-body problem for other applications).
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] *N*-body simulations are widely used tools in astrophysics, from investigating the dynamics of few-body systems like the Earth-Moon-Sun system to understanding the evolution of the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] In physical cosmology, *N*-body simulations are used to study processes of non-linear structure formation such as galaxy filaments and galaxy halos from the influence of dark matter.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Direct *N*-body simulations are used to study the dynamical evolution of star clusters.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The 'particles' treated by the simulation may or may not correspond to physical objects which are particulate in nature.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] For example, an N-body simulation of a star cluster might have a particle per star, so each particle has some physical significance.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] This quantity need not have any physical significance, but must be chosen as a compromise between accuracy and manageable computer requirements.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Dark matter plays an important role in the formation of galaxies.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] In the equation, $\mathbf {v}$ is the velocity, and Φ is the gravitational potential given by Poisson's Equation.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] These two coupled equations are solved in an expanding background Universe, which is governed by the Friedmann equations, after determining the initial conditions of dark matter particles.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The conventional method employed for initializing positions and velocities of dark matter particles involves moving particles within a uniform Cartesian lattice or a glass-like particle configuration.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] This is done by using a linear theory approximation or a low-order perturbation theory.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] In direct gravitational *N*-body simulations, the equations of motion of a system of *N* particles under the influence of their mutual gravitational forces are integrated numerically without any simplifying approximations.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] These calculations are used in situations where interactions between individual objects, such as stars or planets, are important to the evolution of the system.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The first purely calculational simulations were then done by Sebastian von Hoerner at the Astronomisches Rechen-Institut in Heidelberg, Germany.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Regularization is a mathematical trick to remove the singularity in the Newtonian law of gravitation for two particles which approach each other arbitrarily close.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Sverre Aarseth's codes are used to study the dynamics of star clusters, planetary systems and galactic nuclei.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Many simulations are large enough that the effects of general relativity in establishing a Friedmann-Lemaitre-Robertson-Walker cosmology are significant.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] This is incorporated in the simulation as an evolving measure of distance (or scale factor) in a comoving coordinate system, which causes the particles to slow in comoving coordinates (as well as due to the redshifting of their physical energy).
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] However, the contributions of general relativity and the finite speed of gravity can otherwise be ignored, as typical dynamical timescales are long compared to the light crossing time for the simulation, and the space-time curvature induced by the particles and the particle velocities are small.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The boundary conditions of these cosmological simulations are usually periodic (or toroidal), so that one edge of the simulation volume matches up with the opposite edge.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Numerical integration is usually performed over small timesteps using a method such as leapfrog integration.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] However all numerical integration leads to errors.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Smaller steps give lower errors but run more slowly.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Leapfrog integration is roughly 2nd order on the timestep, other integrators such as Runge–Kutta methods can have 4th order accuracy or much higher.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] One of the simplest refinements is that each particle carries with it its own timestep variable, so that particles with widely different dynamical times don't all have to be evolved forward at the rate of that with the shortest time.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] There are two basic approximation schemes to decrease the computational time for such simulations.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] These can reduce the computational complexity to O(N log N) or better, at the loss of accuracy.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] To prevent the simulation from becoming swamped by computing particle-particle interactions, the cells must be refined to smaller cells in denser parts of the simulation which contain many particles per cell.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] For simulations where particles are not evenly distributed, the well-separated pair decomposition methods of Callahan and Kosaraju yield optimal O(*n* log *n*) time per iteration with fixed dimension.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Another possibility is the particle mesh method in which space is discretised on a mesh and, for the purposes of computing the gravitational potential, particles are assumed to be divided between the surrounding 2x2 vertices of the mesh.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] where *G* is Newton's constant and $\rho$ is the density (number of particles at the mesh points).
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] where ${\vec {k}}$ is the comoving wavenumber and the hats denote Fourier transforms.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Since ${\vec {g}}=-{\vec {\nabla }}\Phi$ , the gravitational field can now be found by multiplying by $-i{\vec {k}}$ and computing the inverse Fourier transform (or computing the inverse transform and then using some other method).
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Since this method is limited by the mesh size, in practice a smaller mesh or some other technique (such as combining with a tree or simple particle-particle algorithm) is used to compute the small-scale forces.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Sometimes an adaptive mesh is used, in which the mesh cells are much smaller in the denser regions of the simulation.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Several different gravitational perturbation algorithms are used to get fairly accurate estimates of the path of objects in the Solar System.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] People often decide to put a satellite in a frozen orbit.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The path of a satellite closely orbiting the Earth can be accurately modeled starting from the 2-body elliptical orbit around the center of the Earth, and adding small corrections due to the oblateness of the Earth, gravitational attraction of the Sun and Moon, atmospheric drag, etc.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] It is possible to find a frozen orbit without calculating the actual path of the satellite.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The path of a small planet, comet, or long-range spacecraft can often be accurately modeled starting from the 2-body elliptical orbit around the Sun, and adding small corrections from the gravitational attraction of the larger planets in their known orbits.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Some characteristics of the long-term paths of a system of particles can be calculated directly.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The actual path of any particular particle does not need to be calculated as an intermediate step.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Such characteristics include Lyapunov stability, Lyapunov time, various measurements from ergodic theory, etc.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Although there are millions or billions of particles in typical simulations, they typically correspond to a real particle with a very large mass, typically 109 solar masses.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] This can introduce problems with short-range interactions between the particles such as the formation of two-particle binary systems.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] As the particles are meant to represent large numbers of dark matter particles or groups of stars, these binaries are unphysical.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] To prevent this, a softened Newtonian force law is used, which does not diverge as the inverse-square radius at short distances.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Most simulations implement this quite naturally by running the simulations on cells of finite size.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] It is important to implement the discretization procedure in such a way that particles always exert a vanishing force on themselves.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] (rather than 1/r) where $\epsilon$ is the softening parameter.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The value of the softening parameter should be set small enough to keep simulations realistic.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Many simulations simulate only cold dark matter, and thus include only the gravitational force.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Incorporating baryons, leptons and photons into the simulations dramatically increases their complexity and often radical simplifications of the underlying physics must be made.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] However, this is an extremely important area and many modern simulations are now trying to understand processes that occur during galaxy formation which could account for galaxy bias.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] On the other hand, if the question is whether the body *eventually* reaches the destination ball, the problem is PSPACE-hard.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] These bounds are based on similar complexity bounds obtained for ray tracing.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] The simplest implementation of N-body simulations where ${\textstyle n\geq 3}$ is a naive propagation of orbiting bodies; naive implying that the only forces acting on the orbiting bodies is the gravitational force which they exert on each other.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] This method is applicable to other types of N-body simulations as well; a simulation of point masses with charges would use a similar method, however the force would be due to attraction or repulsion by interaction of electric fields.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Additionally, `OrbitalEntity` contains enough room for a mass value.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Commonly, N-body simulations will be systems based on some type of equations of motion; of these, most will be dependent on some initial configuration to "seed" the simulation.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] In systems such as those dependent on some gravitational or electric potential, the force on a simulation entity is independent on its velocity.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Hence, to seed the *forces* of the simulation, merely initial positions are needed, but this will not allow propagation- initial velocities are required.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Consider a planet orbiting a star- it has no motion, but is subject to gravitational attraction to its host star.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] As a time progresses, and time *steps* are added, it will gather velocity according to its acceleration.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] For a given instant in time, $t_{n}$ , the resultant acceleration of a body due to its neighbouring masses is independent of its velocity, however, for the time step $t_{n+1}$ , the resulting change in position is significantly different due the propagation's inherent dependency on velocity.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] Without acceleration, ${\textstyle {\vec {v}}_{t_{n}}}$ is static, however, from the perspective of an observer seeing only position, it will take two time steps to see a change in velocity.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] A solar-system-like simulation can be accomplished by taking average distances of planet equivalent point masses from a central star.
[src:n-body-simulation/n-body-simulation] To keep code simple, a non-rigorous approach based on semi-major axes and mean velocities will be used.
