[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] In mathematics, a **symplectic integrator** (**SI**) is a numerical integration scheme for Hamiltonian systems.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] Symplectic integrators form the subclass of geometric integrators which, by definition, are canonical transformations.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] They are widely used in nonlinear dynamics, molecular dynamics, discrete element methods, accelerator physics, plasma physics, quantum physics, and celestial mechanics.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] The set of position and momentum coordinates $(q,p)$ are called canonical coordinates.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] The time evolution of Hamilton's equations is a symplectomorphism, meaning that it conserves the symplectic 2-form $dp\wedge dq$ .
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] A numerical scheme is a symplectic integrator if it also conserves this 2-form.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] Symplectic integrators possess, as a conserved quantity, a Hamiltonian which is slightly perturbed from the original one.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] By virtue of these advantages, the SI scheme has been widely applied to the calculations of long-term evolution of chaotic Hamiltonian systems ranging from the Kepler problem to the classical and semi-classical simulations in molecular dynamics.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] Most of the usual numerical methods, such as the primitive Euler scheme and the classical Runge–Kutta scheme, are not symplectic integrators.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] A widely used class of symplectic integrators is formed by the splitting methods.
[src:n-body-simulation/symplectic-integrator] This happens frequently in Hamiltonian mechanics, with T being the kinetic energy and V the potential energy.
